Sales fell to 1.84 million cars last month across the European Union and European Free Trade Area, paring first-quarter growth to 0.6%, the Brussels-based group said. Momentum is starting to slow in some markets and especially in the United Kingdom,” ACEA said in a statement. Nissan’s sales tumbled 16.3% in March, with Ford down 14.6% and Fiat Chrysler 8% lower as the Fiat brand sagged 12%, more than offsetting a 42% surge in Jeep sales. Volkswagen Group sales were little changed, while Renault fell 3.2%. PSA Group recorded a 1.4% gain for its Peugeot unit and a 3.7% decline for Citroen.

--Reuters-- 